He quoted a passage from "Salem's Lot" describing the house inhabited by the vampire of the story but he never used any "haunted" or "creepy" adjectives. It's not too difficult once you understand how it works. AIs like ChatGPT are Large Language Models, and the name gives it away: they are trained to model language. In other words, they are given a ton of text scraped from the internet and learn to both complete "what text comes next" and "fill in the blank" in a way that mimics real human text.

Knowing that, to figure out what to prompt the AI to get the results you want, you just have to think about what text might come before those results if a human wrote them. In a ChatGPT scenario, you can imagine what messages from one person (you) might cause specific types of messages from the other person (the AI). In a less restricted environment that's not limited to chat, such as the base GPT, you just start off with an intro to the results and let the AI complete it with the results themselves.

The one caveat to keep in mind is that ChatGPT has a prefix given to the AI before you ever write anything, to prime it so it knows what to do with your messages. Think of it like an intro that you didn't get to write. It's something like "you're a helpful and kind AI and this is your chat with a person" (but more detail). The preamble, as it's called, is publicly available, so you just need to make sure that you consider it when writing your own prompts, and realize your first message is actually the second part of what the AI reads.

(This preamble is not used in the base GPT, only ChatGPT, meaning it's often easier to get the results you want from GPT than from Chat, since the only text it's completing is yours with no interference.)
